<HEADLINE> Talks Between Ugandan, Sudanese Leaders Makes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Progress was made today in
talks between Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and his Sudanese
Counterpart Omar al-Bashir, South African President Nelson
Mandela, host of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
The high-level discussions also focussed on the need for peace
in strife-torn Sudan, Mandela said in Pretoria. But he declined
to give more details.
</P>
<P>
Bashir and Museveni declined to make comment.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Presidentn Robert Mugabe, who attended in his
capacity as chairman of the Organization for African Unity, also
agreed to keep the meeting result secret, saying, "we still need
to move forward and must therefore retain confidentiality."
</P>
<P>
Relations between Sudan and Uganda have been soured by
accusations that they are backing each others' rebel movements.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said earlier in the day that the meeting had been held
at Bashir's request. When he subsequently raised the matter with
Museveni, the Ugandan president suggested Sudanese People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) leader John Garang also be invited.
</P>
<P>
Garang arrived in South Africa on Wednesday and met Mandela in
Cape Town the next day. However, he refused to have meeting with
his rival Bashir due to be held in Pretoria today. He said his
army would continue war against the Sudanese government. Garang
left for home on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Christian SPLA, which controls a greater part of southern
Sudan, has been at war with Khartoum to fight for greater
autonomy or independence from the Islamic north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
