<HEADLINE> Parents in Tanzania Urged to Help in Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian government
official today called upon parents to cooperate with the
government to fight against the moral decay among the youths.
</P>
<P>
Government rules and regulations alone are not enough to
reform a youth's behavior, and "we must cooperate in solving the
problem which is on the increase," Tanzanian Deputy Minister for
Labor and Youth Development W. Lukuvi said today when closing a
three-week seminar on "good advice to youth" here.
</P>
<P>
Lukuvi said that most of the Tanzanian youths do not want to
use their energy for the social development activities. They are
lazy and they always dream to have a luxury life, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
Though unemployment contributes a lot to a moral decay, Lukuvi
maintained, employment does not mean every body works in office
but employment means any legal business enable a person to get
his daily meal.
</P>
<P>
"If every youth would work hard, I am sure our country would
not be poor as it is now," Lukuvi noted.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the participants to make sufficient research to
investigate the causes of moral decay. He also appealed to
non-governmental institutions to join the government in fighting
against the moral decay among youths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
