<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Visit Iran in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
TEHRAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
is to make his first trip to Iran in December to attend the summit
of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), a senior U.N.
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary general himself will be coming here for the OIC
conference in December," James Speth, administrator of the United
nations Development Program (UNDP), told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Speth, who was on a two-day visit here, said he had met with
Iran's new President Mohammad Khatami and was impressed by his
personality and his program of action for Iran's development.
</P>
<P>
"Khatami is committed to the idea of equitable and sustainable
development espoused by UNDP," Speth said, and he is dedicated to
growth, not just for the rich, but for the average people" as well.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won the May presidential election with a landslide
victory and was sworn in on August 4.
</P>
<P>
Speth said although Iran says 17 percent of its population live
in poverty, U.N. figures show some 22 percent of Iranians are under
the powerty line.
</P>
<P>
Iran has made great strides in fighting poverty, but it is still
lagging behind, Speth said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if UNDP could work better with Khatami's government
which has been dubbed as "moderate", Speth said his agency has never
been swayed by changes in the governments.
</P>
<P>
"Our assistance has never depended on the changes in the
regimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Speth, the total UNDP financial assistance to be
mobilized from 1997 to 1999 amounts to 48 million U.S. dollars,
which will be spent in the areas of social and economic reforms and
enviroment protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
