<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Recieves Messages From US, Russian FMs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today received messages on the Mideast peace stalemate from
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine albright and Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeniy Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency (MENA) said that Albright's message
dealt with the current conditions of the Mideast peace process and
here projected tour of the region in September.
</P>
<P>
The message of the Russsian foreign minister focused on the
peace process in the region and Moscow's role, MENA said, without
giving details.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Russian ambassadors to Egypt delivered the messages
during their separate meetings with Moussa today.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process that started under the co-sponsorship
of Washington and Moscow in 1991 has run into a deep crisis since March
when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Russia, as a major player in commencing the peace process, has
significantly lowered its profile; the U.S. has been widely
criticized for being "too passive" in breaking the peace impasse and
"too biased" in mediating a conciliation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ambassador here Edward Walker told the press after his
meeting with Moussa that Egypt would be the "third or fourth stop" of
Albright's multi-leg tour of the region, which is reportedly to
begin September 9.
</P>
<P>
The maiden trip to the region by Albright would also take her to
Israel, the Palestinian self-rule territories, Syria, Jordan and
possibly Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Walker said further withdrawal of israeli troops from the West
Bank, among other issues, would be discussed during Albright's
visit. Israel declared on Satuday that it will not execute the
second stage of the Oslo accords related to its redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Albright, in an attempt to revive the stalled peace talks, was
reported to bring with her major U.S. initiatives on the final
status talks between Israel and the Palestinians, further Israeli
redeployment and Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
Since talking office in January, Albright has avoided touring
the region, apparently fearing she could achieve little as relations
between Israel and the Palestinians have gone from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
But after the suicide bombings in Jerusalem last month, she was
stongly considering a trip, her aides said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
