<HEADLINE> Phosphate-Loaded Barge Sinks in Nile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A barge ferrying 370 tonnes of
phophate sank into the Nile after it collided with another barge,
the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The barge El-Salam, which belongs to the River Transport Co.,
sank Saturday night near the village of Diyadiya, Beni Suef, about
100 kilometers south of Cairo after hitting another barge carrying
stones.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers had pulled up all six crew on board and were trying to
drag the barge out of water to prevent the river from being polluted.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Public Wroks and Water
Resources assured that the situation has been bring under control and
the accident poses no serious threat to Nile water.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian authorities have closed several outlets on the
lower branches of the Nile to forestall any pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Nile river, which is the longest in the world and runs
about 1,500 kilometers inside Egypt, is the lifeline of Egyptians
on whose banks and delta up to 95 percent of the population are living.
</P>
<P>
The official, on condition of anonymity, said that surrounding
waters, fish and the micro-econsystem in the area will not be
seriously affected thanks to the fact that the 370 tonnes of
phosphates were tightly packed in plastic bags impermeable to water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
