<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Sign Agreement on Aqaba Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
AMMAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel signed today an
agreement for joint operation of the Aqaba international airport in
Jordan's Red Sea port city of Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Jordanian Minister of Transport and
Telecommunications Bassam Saket and his Israeli counterpart Yitzhak
Levy, is the second major breakthrough in further carrying out the
1994 peace treaty, preceded by direct transport of goods between the
two countries in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Details of the joint operation have not been disclosed, but both
sides reportedly agreed early this month that some
international flights to Israeli Red Sea resort Eilat will be
diverted to Aqaba airport from September to alleviate the pressure
on the Eilat airport which has a limited capacity.
</P>
<P>
Joint operation of the Aqaba airport is expected to build
further confidence between the two countries, Radio Jordan quoted
Jasser Ziyyad, Jordan's Civil Aviation Authority Director as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
It would also help boost the regional economy by increasing air
transport, Ziyyad added.
</P>
<P>
Talks on the joint operation of Aqaba airport started at the
beginning of the year, but came to a deadlock in midway following a
set of Israeli conditions which Jordan considered as infringements
on its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
As to the disputes in this aspect, Ziyyad sadi that both sides
would try to overcome the technical and other problems that might
arise during the first phase of operation.
</P>
<P>
The Aqaba airport is the only one in the southern region of the
kingdom that conforms to the international runway standards,
permitting large number of planes to take off and land.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two countries in the Arab world that has
signed peace treaty and set up diplomatic relationship with the
Jewish stae. The other one is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World University Games End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CATANIA, Sicily, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The 19th World University
Games ended here today with the United States finishing on top of the
gold medal table.
</P>
<P>
The Americans got 20 gold, 19 silver and 22 bronze medals, followed
by Ukraine in the second place with 17 gold, 6 silver and 4 bronze.
Japan came third with 14 gold medals and 8 silver and 11 bronze
medals.
</P>
<P>
The 13-day games, the largest sports event second only to Olympic
Games, are more a gathering of student athletes from all over the
world than a top-level international sports competition.
</P>
<P>
The games featured in 10 sports of swimming, diving, fencing,
athletics, water polo, gymnastics (including rhythmic gymnastics),
basketball, volleyball, tennis and soccer.
</P>
<P>
Swimming and athletics were the only two sports in the games which
had their records. But in the competitions, only a few Universiade
records were broken or even challenged while all of the results of the
winners were far behind the world records.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which left its best swimmers at home, still managed to win 9
gold medals to top the medal table of swimming tournament. That was
because the other swimming world powerhouses the United States,
Australia, Germany and Russia only fielded their pure amateur swimmers
to the games while China simply didn't send a single one swimmer to
Sicily Universiade.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese diving team, which dominated the diving tournament by
taking 5 out of 8 gold medals on offer, was consisted of young and
unknown divers who could be unfamiliar even to Chinese sports fans.
</P>
<P>
Yet Chi Meilan, who finished 14th in China's national Champions
Cup, still grasped the women's platform gold with a great advantage of
more than 50 points than all her foreign opponents.
</P>
<P>
The athletics competitions were boosted with the entries of a
handful of world championships and Olympic medalists. But even Ivan
Pedroso of Cuba, the reigning world champion of men's long jump, could
not give the spectators an exciting show.
</P>
<P>
Even the World Sprint Festival, which was held on the last two days
of the Universiade, could hardly satisfy the Sicilian fans. Ottey,
Devers, Frank Fredericks and other stars put up a disappointing
performance compared with their fame.
</P>
<P>
The only real good result of the games came from American Vincent
Henderson who clocked 9.94 seconds in the men's 100 meters
semi-finals. But he only clocked 10.22 seconds in the final to win
the title due to leg hamstring.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the competition results, the organising works of the
games were better. But the organising committee had to work hard to
slove the problems of transportation, communication and computer
system even on the closing day of the games.
</P>
<P>
As the games were the first one held in three cities and many more
towns, the organising committee had more difficulties than even
Olympic organisers.
</P>
<P>
So, we should say that the games were a success, which owed a great
deal to two millions spectators following all the different sports
with a strong passion.
</P>
<P>
Primo Nebiolo, president of the FISU, said at a press conference
that all the foreign athletes would remember Sicily's warmness.
</P>
<P>
Nebiolo, also president of the International Amateur Athletics
Federation (IAAF), said: "Nowhere else in the world the athletes have
been welcomed as has happened this time in Sicily."
</P>
<P>
The next Universiade will be held in Palma of Spain in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
