<HEADLINE> Cameroun's Engineers Urge Govt to Revive Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Cameroun Society of
Engineers (CSE) has called on the government to revive the
trans-African highway project as a step toward economic
development of the nation, Radio Cameroun reported today.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in a resolution adopted in Yaounde on
Saturday at the end of the two-day 30th anniversary convention of
the CSE.
</P>
<P>
The CSE also said the trans-African telecommunication network
should be revived so as to work toward universal access to
telecommunication. It called on greater emphasis to be given to
other aspects of engineering.
</P>
<P>
According to experts at the convention, the CSE can with the
help of the government make the country advance technically. The
CSE will also engage the government in constructive dialogue to
discuss the issues raised in the convention.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the convention on Friday,
Cameroun's Minister of Public Works Jean Bokam pointed out that
it is necessary for the engineering society to collaborate with
the government to create conditions favorable to the growth of
home-based engineering companies. 
</P>
