<HEADLINE> Australia Foreign Debt Surges to 150 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia's net foreign debt
rose to 202.024 billion Australian dollars (about 150 billion U.S.
dollars) in the June quarter from a revised 197.67 billion
Australian dollars (146.3 billion U.S. dollars) in the March
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The figure also compares with 187.53 billion Australian dollars
(138.9 billion U.S. dollars) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
This represents a 2.2 percent increase in the net debt within
three months, the Australian Bureau of Statistics said today.
</P>
<P>
Gross debt rose to 254.687 billion dollars (about 189.74
billion U.S. dollars) in the June quarter from a revised 247.819
billion dollars (183.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the March quarter
and 236.012 billion dollars (175.3 billion U.S. dollars) a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Peter Costello defended the federal government's
record, as foreign debt levels surged above the 200 billion mark.
</P>
<P>
Costello told parliament that he still expected the foreign
debt level to fall as the government returned the budget to
surplus.
</P>
<P>
Costello blamed the high level of foreign debt on the previous
Labor Government, which he said had allow debt levels to grow
from 23 billion (17 billion U.S. dollars) to 187 billion
Australian dollars (138.9 billion U.S. dollars) in 13 years
between 1983 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
"If we had inherited 23 billion dollars as you did we would not
be in the exposed position we are now," he said in answer to a
question from Opposition spokesman Gareth Evens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
