<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Budget Surplus of 900 Million Pesos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Budget Secretary Salvador
Enriquez said today that the Philippine government would generate
a budget surplus of 900 million pesos (30 million U.S. dollars)
this year from the depreciation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
After having calculating the impact of the peso's depreciation
on revenues and expenditures, budget officials computed that the
income was bigger by 900 million pesos over net expenditures, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Enriquez said the budget officials are looking for creative
ways of living up to the depreciated peso.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to live with the value of the depreciated peso in
a way that continues the frugal and prudent program of the
government. We will not hike the budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is also looking at ways of keeping
project costs within the existing budget despite the depreciated
peso.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure projects like roads and bridges, hit by lower
peso value because of the use of imported construction materials,
will have to be cheaper but not inferior in quality, Enriquez
said.
</P>
<P>
The budget officials would learn how to construct cheaper
bridges with better or creative ways of reducing the cost, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The peso has depreciated by 14 percent after it was floated
within a wider band by the country's Central Bank on July 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
