<HEADLINE> Japan Conducts Major Earthquake Drills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan today conducted
large-scale earthquake drills to boost disaster preparedness.
</P>
<P>
The drills, which emphasized coordination of various government
agencies' functions, were held on the premise that strong
earthquakes had struck the Tokai and southern Kanto regions.
</P>
<P>
The Fire Defense Agency estimated that a total of 7.97 million
people took part in the exercises.
</P>
<P>
Included were school children and business people who held
concurrent drills testing their own ability to cope with such a
calamity.
</P>
<P>
The drills assumed that an offshore earthquake, registering
eight on the Richter scale, struck the Tokai region in the
morning, while a 7.2 magnitude temblor occurred directly beneath
Yokohama in the afternoon, rocking the southern part of the Kanto
region.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto flew into Yokohama by
helicopter this afternoon and observed anti-disaster drills there.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, about 30 volunteer interpreters of six foreign
languages, including English and Chinese, joined in the drills.
</P>
<P>
In Fujieda, Shizuoka Prefecture, about 7,300 local residents as
well as Self-Defense Forces personnel took part in disaster relief
drills under the observation of a central government research team.
</P>
<P>
The drills were held as part of a series of anti-disaster
drills during Japan's Disaster Prevention Week, which runs from
Saturday to the following Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
