<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mozambique in Economic Revival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique, after 16
years of civil war which had reduced it to one of the world's
poorest nations, was experiencing a revival by poising for eight
percent economic growth and much lower inflation.
</P>
<P>
Mozambiuqe's economic reforms have been described by the World
Bank as a success story, with an eight percent growth last year.
</P>
<P>
According to official figure, the government has brought
annual inflation down to 14 percent from 70 percent three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
"Mozambique is in the process of a remarkable recovery, we are
enjoying social and political stability," said Jose Luis Cabaco,
a Mozambican economist based in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We have made remarkable progress in lowering inflation and
forecast our Gross Domestic Product (GDP) to grow by eight
percent this year if we receive as good rains as last year."
</P>
<P>
President Joaquim Chissano told the press last weekend that
his government is carrying out a comprehensive restructuring
program to rehabilitate the basic structure.
</P>
<P>
Much of the growth would come from power export from the
Cahora Bassa Dam to South Africa and Zimbabwe, which was
scheduled to start in October next year.
</P>
<P>
The electricity exports are expected to bring in about 100
million U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment and the privatisation program, which
started in 1989, were also expected to boost the country's GDP.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign investment projects will also have a
positive impact on the national economy this year.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government had earmarked 700 public enterprises
for privatisation. Last year, 34.7 million U.S. Dollars was
raised from the sale of 22 state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government hopes to sale off 15 large public
enterprises, with the disposal of 350 smaller companies expected
to run into 1998.
</P>
<P>
The privatisation program has led to the creation of 69 new
companies and has had a huge impact on the cement, beverages,
metal working and packaging sectors.
</P>
<P>
Although Mozambique was experiencing an economic upswing, it
remained saddled with high unemployment, with unofficial
estimates putting the figure of the urban unemployment at 65
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
