<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actions Urged to Lighten Hong Kong School Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Education
Department officials today called for actions to reduce the weight
of local school bags.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the department are concerned about overweight
school bags, in particular their possible harmful effects on the
formation of spines on primary and junior secondary school
students.
</P>
<P>
It is important to have measures taken to tackle the problem
and obtain support and cooperation from schools, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Under a set of updated guidelines, students are encouraged to
develop the habit of packing school bags every day and discouraged
from taking toys, magazines and unnecessary items to schools.
</P>
<P>
Schools should advise students on the types of school bags and
on the correct posture in carrying them.
</P>
<P>
Parents' cooperation and support should be sought so that the
advice given to students at schools will be reinforced at home,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Timetables should be designed to enable students not to take a
large number of textbooks, workbooks or exercise books to school
on any day of the week or cycle.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, schools should consider the weight and size
of textbooks before determining which textbooks should be
prescribed and avoid too many supplementary workbooks and
additional exercise books.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also suggested schools provide students with
drinking water and facilities such as lockers, as far as possible,
to store books, stationery and personal items.
</P>
<P>
They also urged teachers to avoid punishing students for
occasionally failing to bring books or other items to class.
</P>
<P>
Schools are encouraged to draw up and implement other measures
which they consider practicable and effective to reduce the weight
of school bags, the officials added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nyerere Likely to Quit Burundi Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's former president
Mwalimu Julius Nyerere is likely to step down as mediator for
Burundi peace talks following Burundi's boycott of the talks last
week in Arusha, northern Tanzania, "The East African" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper said Nyerere might put forward the offer at
the regional heads of state summit to be held this week in Dar es
Salaam, capital of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The proposed summit is expected to review Burundi's progress
in meeting conditions imposed by the region last July after Major
Buyoya seized power in a coup by the Tutsi-dominated army.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Nyerere made his quit offer to Burundi
through South African special envoy Ambassador Wolile Nhlapo.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere was apparently angered by Buyoya's snubbing of the
Arusha meeting as without Bujumbura's participation, his mandate
to continue with the talks would be seriously undermined.
</P>
<P>
In a note to all its diplomatic missions abroad sent on the
very day of the aborted talks, the Buyoya regime accused Nyerere
of making provocative statements which further strained relations
between Tanzania and Burundi and discouraged participation in
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has also raised misgivings about Tanzania's role as a
host for the talks at a time when the tension in the relations
between the two neighbouring countries is running high.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has refused to recognize the Buyoya
regime since the bloodless coup which returned him to power last
July and accused Burundi of planning an invasion into its
territory.
</P>
<P>
In a two-hour meeting with Buyoya, special envoy Nhlapo said
that if Arusha was not acceptable as a talks venue to all sides,
then another country should be asked to host the talks, the paper
noted.
</P>
<P>
The paper disclosed that Burundi would send a team this week
to Harare, Zimbabwe, to present Burundi's case directly to
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, current chairman of the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The team would reportedly send a message to Mugabe, saying
that Burundi would like to see Nyerere step down as mediator for
the Burundi peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
