<HEADLINE> Dutch Hooligans Sentenced To Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Two soccer hooligans were
convicted of homicide and sentenced to four years in prison in
Haarlem, 15 kilometers west of Amsterdam on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two Ajax fans took part in the riot in March that killed a
supporter of a rival squad.
</P>
<P>
The fight, which was involved hundreads of fans from archrivals
Ajax Amsterdam and Feyenoord Rotterdam, was one of the worst
violence in Dutch soccer history. Fans attacked each other. They
also destroyed and torched nearby cars.
</P>
<P>
The two defendants, identified only as Marco P. and Leonardo
P., were convicted by the Haarlem District Court of homicide in
the fatal beating of Ajax fan Carlo Picornie.
</P>
<P>
Picornie was beaten, stabbed and left to die in a field during
the battle on March 23.
</P>
<P>
The court also sentenced six other Feyenoord fans for being
involved in the violence. Their jail sentences ranged from six
months to three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
