<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Talk of a cut in official
interest rates this week filtered through the market, causing the
Australian dollar to drift to a lower close against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed in Sydney at 73.15 U.S. cents, down
from 73.44 locally late on Friday, after trading today in a tight
range of 73.10 to 73.25 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Rumors surfaced last week that the Reserve Bank of Australia,
the country's central bank, could move as soon as on Wednesday,
after its September board meeting tomorrow, to cut the official
cash rate for the sixth time since July last year.
</P>
<P>
The cash rate currently stands at 5.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Moore, the foreign exchange trading manager with the St
George Bank, said today there had not been a lot of activity in
Australia's foreign exchange market and not much was expected
tonight because the U.S. markets would be shut for the Labor Day
holiday there.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 88.45 Japanese yen, from
87.37 while against the German mark, it was at 1.3289, from
1.3187.  
</P>
</TEXT>
