<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Changes Little </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
was left little changed by the quietest trading day since December
27, 1996, holding its breath and insecurity about Asian financial
markets' volatility and recent equity falls in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Investor enthusiasm was also sapped by the Labor Day long
weekend in the U.S., with half a day trading on Friday and a full
holiday later in the global day today.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries finished down 2.2 points to 2,590.8 on the
back of national turnover of 197.25 million shares worth 412.26
million Australian dollars (305.07 million U.S. dollars). Falls of
534 outnumbered rises of 408.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 2.9 points to 4,174.3, compared
to a drop of 1.8 points to 1,355.4 in the all resources index.
</P>
<P>
Soft drink giant Coca-Cola Amatil was drained by concern about
the Asian markets, falling 32.1 cents to 13.559 Australian
dollars, a five-month closing low.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 percent of Coca-Cola Amatil's earnings come from its
newly acquired Coca-Cola Bottlers Philippines Inc (CCBPI) of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Bellwether BHP slipped 4.4 cents to 17.036 Australian dollars
after the group said on Saturday that it wants to raise investment
in downstream steel processing facilities across the world.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 4.3 points to 1,309.5 after the gold
price recovered today to 324.75 U.S. dollars an ounce in late
Sydney trading. The bullion price had slipped to 324.15 U.S.
dollars in early trading in Sydney today, from 324.70 last night.
</P>
<P>
Among the interest rate sensitive stocks, Commonwealth Bank
dropped 19 cents to 14.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ, another national bank, was down three to 9.75 Australian
dollars, National Australia Bank fell one cent to 18.89 Australian
dollars, but Westpac managed to lift 0.4 cent to 7.894 Australian
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
