<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Tea Likely to Make Good Profit this Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's tea industry is
expecting substantial profits this year because of higher prices
in the international market despite a slight fall in production
due to inadequate rains, according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian country produced 30 million kilograms in the
first eight months of this year as against the whole year target
of 54 million kilograms, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
This year's average quoted price is 74 taka (about 1.68 U.S.
dollars) per kilogram, the highest for 10 years. It was 65 taka
(about 1.48 dollars) per kilogram last year.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our companies would make significant profit as the
increased price in the international market is expected to be
sustained in the coming days," said Syed Hasib, director of the
Bangladesh Tea Board.
</P>
<P>
The tea output for the whole year would fall short of the
targeted 54 million kilograms, but could still manage to reach
around 51 million kilograms if the weather is good, Hasib said.
</P>
<P>
The total tea production last year was 53.50 million kilograms,
of which 26.14 million kilograms were exported, earning 1.35
billion taka (about 30.68 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh now has 158 tea estates with a total area of 112,464
hectares, of which 47,938 hectares are planted to tea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
