<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Defense Minister Leaves For Geneva on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Deputy Prime
Minister and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah
left for Geneva today to attend a two-day meeting on the
controversial issue of Kuwaiti Prisoners of War (POWs) in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insists that more than 600 Kuwaiti POWs have been held
in Iraq since the end of the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed official from Kuwaiti defense ministry was quoted by
the Kuwait News Agency as saying the minister would press hard at
the Geneva meeting, which is sponsored by the Tripartite
Committee, for the release of the Kuwaiti POWs.
</P>
<P>
The official said Iraq has failed to comply with a host of
U.N. Security Council resolutions related to its aggression in
Kuwait including a call for the immediate release of the POWs.
</P>
<P>
The Tripartite Committee, sponsored by the International
Committee of the Red Cross following the Gulf War, groups Kuwait,
Iraq as well as the Gulf War allied anti-Iraq countries such as
Saudi Arabia, the U.S., Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
So far a total of 25 meetings, once a month at the
Kuwaiti-Iraqi border, have been held by a technical sub-committee
of the Tripartite Committee, but failed to achieve any results
due to difference on the POWs issue between Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait claimed that the POWs who were brought to Iraq at the
end of the Gulf War are still being detained in Iraqi jails while
Baghdad denied it still jails these people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq acknowledged taking some POWs to Iraq along with
withdrawing troops, but it claimed having no fresh information
about their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
It said a number of the Kuwaiti POWs had gone missing during a
popular uprising that broke out in southern Iraq following the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The POWs issue has been one of the key factors hindering any
improvement of relations between Kuwait and Iraq within the
framework of an Arab reconciliation campaign in which Kuwait
started to restore normal ties this year with countries such as
Jordan, Sudan and Yemen which sided with Iraq during the Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
