<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets British Educationalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing said today that China has taken a positive attitude
towards international exchanges in higher education.
</P>
<P>
The increase in exchanges between institutions of higher
education in China and Britain is of great significance at the
time when the world is approaching the 21st century, Li Lanqing
said.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Premier made the remarks at a meeting with two British
education delegations in Zhongnanhai, the site of the central
government.
</P>
<P>
The British higher education delegations is led by Professor
Brian Fender, chief executive of Higher Education Founding Council
for England, and the British university presidents delegation is
led by James Wright.
</P>
<P>
The two delegations are here to attend the symposium of Chinese
and British university presidents. The symposium to be held in the
coming two days is scheduled to focus on the status and role of
the institutions of higher education in promoting scientific
development, challenges and policies facing institutions of higher
education in current society, as well as the quality strategy for
universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
