<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.K. Seeks Constructive Working Ties With S.E. Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain is seeking to
strengthen and deepen its relations with countries in Southeast
Asia, particularly in the areas of economic cooperation, visiting
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I've come here early in the life of the Labor Government
precisely because we want to demonstrate our recognition of the
importance of this region and the priority we've attached to
building constructive working relations with countries of this
region," Cook said at a press conference before winding up his
six-day Southeast Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting on the tour, which had already taken him to
Malaysia, Indonesia, and the Philippines, Robin noted that this
was the first major visit to Southeast Asia by a British Foreign
Secretary for a decade.
</P>
<P>
"I think it particularly significant that I've carried out this
visit despite the recent financial turbulence, because it
demonstrates our faith that the economic fundamentals of Southeast
Asia are strong, and that in the medium and long term, this region
will be a place of growing economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook recalled that in the course of his visit, he had explored
in every capital how Britain and these countries could strengthen
and deepen their economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I can say that in the course of this visit, we have managed to
achieve a balanced dialogue with the countries of the region both
on how we develop economic cooperation to our mutual benefit, and
on how we also talk openly and honestly to each other about our
concerns so that we better understand each other's perspectives,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who arrived here on Sunday, has met with Senior Minister
Lee Kuan Yew, Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong and Foreign Minister S Jayakumar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
