<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Approves Income Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate today
approved on second reading the last component of the Comprehensive
Tax Reform Program setting the new income tax system for corporate
and individual taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
The measure is expected to generate 2 billion pesos (66.7
million U.S. dollars) in revenues for the government, despite an
increase in exemptions granted to individual taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Among the amendments to the income tax payments introduced in
the program are a rise in personal exemption granted to individual
taxpayers to 20,000 pesos (666.7 dollars).
</P>
<P>
It also increased from four to five the number of qualified
dependent children who are entitled to a 6,500-pesos (216.7
dollars) allowance.
</P>
<P>
The bill likewise raised to 40,000 pesos (1,333 dollars) the
exempted income from tax, representing bonuses received annually,
subject to adjustments based on inflation, as approved by the
finance secretary.
</P>
<P>
A 2,400-peso (80 dollars) deduction for actual tuition fees
paid per family with an income level of not more than 150,000
pesos (5,000 dollars) shall be granted, plus a 2,600-peso (86.7
dollars) deduction for actual and medical hospitalization expenses
per family.
</P>
<P>
Another 2,400-peso (80 dollars) exemption shall also be given
to the premium for health and hospitalization insurance per family
with income of not more than 250,000 pesos (8,333 dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
