<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Banks in Thailand See Deposits Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Banks in Thailand are seeing
major reshuffles of deposits among them amid uncertainties about
the country's entire financial sector, with small banks facing a
run on their deposits.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics by the Research Institute of Siam
Commercial Bank, deposits with Thailand's 15 banks totaled 3.845
trillion baht (about 128.1 billion U.S. dollars) in July, up 1.77
percent from June.
</P>
<P>
Large local commercial banks saw deposits grow, though slowly,
during the month. Bangkok Bank obtained the largest deposits in
the country, which were posted at 863.49 billion baht (28.78
billion dollars) in July, up 2.34 percent from June.
</P>
<P>
Krung Thai Bank recorded deposits of 547.71 billion baht (18.26
billion dollars), a rise of 1.89 percent from June, and ranked
second in terms of deposits amount, followed by Thai Farmers Bank
with deposits amounting to 505.72 billion baht (16.86 billion
dollars), 1.29 percent more than June.
</P>
<P>
Siam Commercial Bank reported a 7.69-percent increase in its
deposits, the biggest margin in the month among the 15 banks,
although its total deposits stood at 466.15 billion baht (16.86
billion dollars) and ranked fourth.
</P>
<P>
Thai Military Bank registered the second largest increase
margin of 6.02 percent in deposits in July, which were 238.99
billion baht (7.97 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, five small and medium-sized banks saw at least 27.9
billion baht (930 million dollars) flow out of their accounts.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Metropolitan Bank reported the largest decrease of
13.37 percent in deposits in July, followed by the country's
smallest bank, Laem Thong Bank, which kept deposits of just 30.87
billion baht (1.03 billion dollars) in the month, down 11.43
percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Central Bank's announcement late June to suspend the
operations of 16 finance firms sparked heavy withdrawals from the
firms and other financial institutions. Depositors or creditors
were shifting their money to those financial institutions which
they believe are safer.
</P>
<P>
Large local commercial banks apparently benefited a lot from
the deposits reshuffles and so did the 19 foreign banks which have
branches in the country.
</P>
<P>
The deposits with the foreign banks in July jumped by 35.42
percent from June to 120.4 billion baht (4 billion dollars),
according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Tokyo's branch in Thailand saw deposits soar to 21.51
billion baht (717 million dollars) in July, up 11.33 percent from
June, ranking first among the 19 foreign banks in terms of
deposits amount.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank posted deposits totaling 20.15 billion
baht (716.6 million dollars) in its branch in Thailand in July, a
rise of 99.91 percent over June.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Bank's branch reported a 181.3-percent increase in
deposits to 10.49 billion baht (349.7 million dollars) in July
from June, although it ranked fifth in terms of deposits amount.
</P>
<P>
Bank of America also witnessed a 115.03-percent increase in
deposits in its branch in Thailand to 4.45 billion baht (148.3
million dollars) in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Some newly-opened branches of foreign banks reported an even
more stunning increase in their deposits in July.
</P>
<P>
Dresdner Bang Ag's branch posted the highest increase of 2,006
percent among the 19 in the month, as deposits with it ballooned
from 13 million baht (430,000 dollars) in June to 274 million baht
(9.1 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank' branch achieved an
increase of 877.09 percent in its deposits to 1.544 billion baht
(51.5 million dollars) in the month.
</P>
<P>
Bank of China also posted a total of 222 million baht (7.4
million dollars) in deposits in July, up 20.03 percent from June.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Central Bank announced to suspend the operations of
additional 42 finance firms in early August, triggering heavier
withdrawals from local financial institutions around the country.
</P>
<P>
Although the August figures are not yet available, analysts
said deposits figures in the month with local and foreign banks
are expected to have bigger changes, with small and medium-sized
banks gaining less deposits and large banks and foreign bank
branches reaping more.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
