Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- A death without objective, a death without words, but with
image: Lady Diana died as she had lived, under the spell of the
dreaming machine. Nothing very normal or very understandable, as
was shown by the reaction of public opinion in front of the end of
a modern and touching young woman.
</P>
<P>
-- The slaughter of 300 civilians on August 29, according to
hospital sources, in Reis, south of Algiers, has brought to an end
of the silence and indifference of the international community
toward the endless conflict in Algeria, and has made Abassi
Madani, the newly released leader of the Islamic Salvation Front,
to agree to appeal for an end of "blood letting" in his country.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- If the death of Princess Diana on Sunday was such a shock,
it is that she seems to be the product of a little forgotten
word: destiny. Nothing but fatality can explain this death which
came suddenly in the full night, full speed, and full glory as
much as those in the mythologies of the epoch.
</P>
<P>
-- In a letter addressed to the United Nations Secretary
General, leader of Algeria's outlawed Islamic Salvation Front
Abassi Madani, who was released two months ago by the Algerian
authorities, promised to immediately launch an appeal for an end
of violence. This came after 100 to 200 people were massacred
assumably by Islamic extremists on August 29 in Algiers. 
</P>
