<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pardon for Ex-Presidents New Political Issue in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Pardon for former South Korean
Presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo has become a major
political issue with the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) beginning to
take concrete steps to release them by the Mid-Autumn Festival
this month.
</P>
<P>
Chun and Roh have been indicted on bribery charges and are
currently serving jail terms as long as a whole life and 22 years
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Party Chairman Lee Hoi-chang will propose a pardon of Chun and
Roh to President Kim Young-sam on September 4," NKP spokesman Lee
Sa-churl said today.
</P>
<P>
The NKP said the pardons are necessary to realize the "grand
political unity," starting to take measures to free them by the
festival beginning on September 15.
</P>
<P>
The move is interpreted as a wooing gesture to Kyongsang
Provinces' voters, the hometowns of the former presidents, in
consideration for the coming presidential election in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
The main opposite National Congress for New Politics (NCNP),
whose president Kim Dae-jung had already suggested the pardon, is
yet to decide on the party's official decision.
</P>
<P>
While the majority of NCNP leaders have accepted Kim Dae-jung's
revised position on the issue, some others called for a more
cautious approach before setting on a final position.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung's original stance was that before the two former
presidents can be pardoned, they should apologize first.
</P>
<P>
But the second biggest opposite United Liberal Democrats (ULD),
while agreeing on the pardon, insisted that the matter should not
be discussed until the presidential election is held and that the
NKP cannot be the one to propose the pardon.
</P>
<P>
After all, the ULD said, it was the NKP who introduced those
special laws so that Chun and Roh could be indicted.
</P>
<P>
The minor opposite Democratic Party also agreed that the former
presidents should be pardoned, but opposed the proposed time.
</P>
<P>
At today's news conference, President of the Democratic Party
Cho Soon called it "regretful" that the two former presidents were
jailed and agreed that they should be pardoned.
</P>
<P>
However, he criticized the NKP for hurrying up to set free the
two ex-presidents by the Mid-Autumn festival, a strategy for the
upcoming presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0069 </DOCNO>
