<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Leaves for Brazil for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
left here today for a 10-day official visit to Brazil which has
the largest population of Lebanese expatriates in the world,
according to radio reports this morning.
</P>
<P>
The visit to Brazil is the first by a Lebanese president in 43
years.
</P>
<P>
The visit is aimed at enhancing bilateral relations and
strengthening ties between Lebanese expatriates in Brazil and
local residents.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi will hold talks with his Brazilian counterpart Fernando
Henrique Cardoso mainly on promoting political and economic
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also tackle the deadlocked Middle East peace
process and the importance of the implementation of U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425 demanding Israeli full withdrawal from its
self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Hrawi will also discuss with the Lebanese
expatriates on the issue of granting Lebanese nationality to
some of them.
</P>
<P>
Some Lebanese expatriates living in Brazil have lost their
Lebanese nationality due to disorder in Lebanon resulted from the
1975-1990 civil war. These expatriates demanded Lebanon to grant
them Lebanese nationality.
</P>
<P>
The number of Lebanese expatriates in Brazil reaches more than
8 million, according to latest official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
