<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Not to Run for President in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today he will not run for president in 2000, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony to start the new school year at Moscow's
No. 1253 School, Yeltsin said, "My term ends in 2000 and I will
not run any more."
</P>
<P>
He told the children that he hoped someone from the school will
grow up to become the president.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin announced earlier today in a radio address that 1,000
presidential grants are annually provided for the best students
and graduate students, including grants for receiving education
in the world's leading universities.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Russia needs specialists in economics, accounting,
law, psychology and programming, saying that "our higher
educational establishments are doing everything to meet this
demand." 
</P>
