<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Organizations Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-eight Greek and
Turkish Cypriot organizations today issued a joint declaration,
calling for a federal, peaceful and democratic Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, issued on the occasion of the International
Day for Peace, described the status quo as the "basis for
provocative actions, friction, conflict and war" on the island.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that it is their "historic duty to oppose those
forces that inhibit peaceful procedures and to work together in
order to secure lasting peace in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over 37 percent of the island in the wake of a
failed Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island nation as a bi-communal, bi-zonal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The organizations said in their declaration that their aim is
the creation of a federal, peaceful and democratic Cyprus, which
will be common home for Greek and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"People should be aware of their past but they should not
live in the past," the declaration said, adding that "we
must find the way to overcome feelings of hatred and revenge and
to make good use of our past experiences in order to build a
peaceful future."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Greek and Turkish Cypriot trade unions
will hold a peace rally this afternoon at the Ledra Palace
checkpoint in Nicosia, organized by the All-Cyprus Trade Union
Forum, to mark the International Day for peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transit Route to Bangladesh via India for Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's long-held dream of
an alternative transit route to Bangladesh via India's Phulbari
came true today as the route was formally inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
Indian ambassador to Nepal K. V. Rajan and Commerce Secretary
of Nepal Mohan Dev Pant exchanged letters today at Kakarbhitta,
formally guaranteeing Nepal's right to the transit route for the
coming six months, said a press release issued by the Indian
embassy.
</P>
<P>
The new land route runs 71 kilometers from Kakarbhitta, Nepal's
eastern gateway to India, to Banglabandh in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
According to the modalities reached by the two sides,
pilfer-proof trucks and containers can use the transit route on
Saturdays and Sundays, and these trucks and containers will be
escorted by the Indian security force and can go only during the
broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
And only 25 trucks at most will be released at one time from
each side.
</P>
<P>
There will be a short negative list of categories of goods not
allowed for transit such as firearms and ammunition, hazardous
cargo, gold and silver bullion and narcotics, the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has requested for this alternative route to Bangladesh
through Phulbari in the so-called "chicken neck" in northeastern
India since it found uneconomic the first transit route granted by
India in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Nepal wants to lessen its dependence on the Calcutta port of
India which is beset with a host of problems.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Nepal in early June, Indian Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral agreed to the request.
</P>
<P>
The transit route, which was conducted on a trial basis, is
subject to review after six months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nepali Commerce Minister Sarbendra Nath Shukla is in
Bangladesh for inaugurating the transit route at Mongla port in
southwestern Bangladesh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
