<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floral Industry Blossoms in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Flower power is packing a
stronger punch in east China's Fujian province, which now ranks
among the country's top seven flower-growing areas.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, the total flower planting area
covers 5,107 ha. and the annual output value has topped 383
million yuan, up 28 percent and nearly four-fold the amount in
1990.
</P>
<P>
The province has made its flower industry a priority in its
agricultural development plan, and individual flower-growers have
organized channels for exchanging information on the business.
</P>
<P>
With the government's help, Luoyuan county has begun to export
flowers. Its annual export to Japan alone has reached one million
bouquets.
</P>
<P>
People living in the southwestern mountainous areas of the
province have developed simple pot-planting into large-scale
flower fields including many major cymbidium production bases.
</P>
<P>
Nankeng Town of Nanjing county has earned over 10 million yuan
annually from flower cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the province is able to provide a wide variety of
flowers in any season.
</P>
<P>
The city of Zhangzhou, known as the hometown of narcissus, has
invested five million yuan to build a flower planting zone. Over
30 domestic and overseas investors have joined the lucrative
business, owing to the preferential policies issued by the local
government.
</P>
<P>
A 50 km-long flower belt, covering over 667 ha. of land, and a
large flower market are to be built along the Zhangzhou section of
the No. 324 state highway.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial officials, Fujian has drawn up plans to
further expand the floral industry. By 2000, the province will
have a total flower-planting area of 66,667 ha., while its yearly
output value is expected to reach 600 million yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maize, Bean Output to Rise in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Maize output in Uganda is
projected to rise to 839,000 metric tons this year, a 10.54
percent increase over the 759,000 tons produced in 1996, the
local daily The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Ministry of Agriculture showed that
currently maize accounts for 17,823,000 U.S. Dollars or 2.7
percent of the country's annual foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Bean output is projected to shoot up to 372,000 metric tons
this year from the 1996 level of 234,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Beans and other legume take up an annual 16,104,000 dollars or
2.4 percent of Uganda's external earnings.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the two crops have a big potential to rake in
more revenue if production is boosted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
