<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Market Creation to Be Delayed in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The establishment of the
proposed secondary bond market in the Philippines will be delayed,
an official of the Capital Market Development Council said today.
</P>
<P>
Jenny Canlas, spokeswoman of the council, traced the reasons to
the intervention of some economic and political forces in the
United Nations-sponsored project.
</P>
<P>
She said the council, in coordination with the government, has
to seriously pay attention to the economic and political
priorities at this time when the capital market is experiencing
speculative attacks resulting in the latest currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Canlas, however, stressed that the members of the council,
composed of top officials from government and the business
sectors, are scheduled to meet again in October to finalize the
implementation of the proposed secondary bond market project.
</P>
<P>
She is optimistic that the meeting would result positively in
the finalization of a number of measures that could eventually
lead to the project's implementation before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project will initially be implemented with a
start-up budget of 33,000 US dollars from the United Nations
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The amount will be used to finance the project's consultations
for experts on the bond market's development like the preparation
of the project feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
In addition to this, proponents of the project, led by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, have recommended to the
Department of Finance for the endorsement of partial funding
support from the Asian Development Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
