<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Overseas Investment for Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, Sepember 1 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, an old heavy
industrial base in northeast China, is expecting more overseas
investment to develop its economy.
</P>
<P>
It has more than 1,400 large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises, a tenth of the country's total, with more than 400
billion yuan (48 billion US dollars) in fixed assets, according to
Gao Guozhu, Deputy Governor of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning plans to use 1.3 billion US dollars in overseas
investment for 83 projects in the petrochemical, metallurgical,
machine-building and electronics sectors, the province's four
pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds will also be used to develop high-tech industries
like computers, new materials, and telecommunications. Another 250
million US dollars will be used for 50 agricultural projects, and
1.36 billion US dollars for 45 tourism projects.
</P>
<P>
There are 163 projects listed as state key technological
improvement projects, with investment expected to reach 482.5
billion yuan, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
The province has established economic ties with 60 big foreign
companies and financial groups like the General Motors of the USA
and Mitsubishi of Japan, he said, adding Liaoning attracted 18.62
billion US dollars in overseas investment in the past four and
half years, accounting for 78.8 percent of the total since the
reform and opening-up drive began in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
