<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Violence Hits Kenya's Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A fortnight of violence in
Kenya's coast districts has dealt a serious blow to the tourism
industry with two hotels closed and workers sent on leave, "The
East African" reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the past two weeks, more than 40 people have been
killed in violent actions in the port city of Mombasa and its
environs which began with a raid on a police station at Likoni
area on August 13.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspapers said that two Italian companies closed
their tourist hotels last week in Malindi, a resort town in
Kenya's coastal region which attracts most of some 770,000
visitors to Kenya each year.
</P>
<P>
Ventag Lia Group closed the 200-bed Temple Point on August 27
because there were no new bookings owing to massive cancellations
by Italian holiday makers while Beach Oasis Ltd. closed the
150-bed Jombo Village.
</P>
<P>
A weekly 5,000 tourists visit Mombasa during the normal travel
season, but now the number has fallen drastically by 30 to 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 charter flights land in Mombasa every week and all
of them were fully booked before the Likoni violence, said the
paper, adding that now many had been cancelled, particularly from
Italy.
</P>
<P>
One hotel chain, which has four units in the Likoni area,
reported that bed occupancy had plummeted from 98 percent two
weeks ago to 37 percent by last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gideon Mung'aro, chairman of the Mombasa and Coast Tourist
Association's Malindi branch, said more than 100 workers of
Malindi's Blue Club Hotel were sent on leave Sunday and over 500
workers in other establishments in the area faced the same fate.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry is the number one foreign exchange earner for
the east African country, which received 770,000 visitors last
year with an earning of 480 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
