<HEADLINE> Live Internet Coverage for Chinese Bridge Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, Southwest Sichuan, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The China
Cup international bridge event will be broadcasted live through
the Internet, the first time in the world for the sport,
organizers said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Anybody who has the access to the World Wide Web in any part of
the world can closely follow the actions in the team competitions
through the web site www.cpisn.cn.net.
</P>
<P>
The team competition will take place in the first three days of
the the September 1-9 event. The rest is individual tourney.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said the event has attracted some international
bridge stars, which include world number one player Lynn Deas.
</P>
<P>
Live Internet coverage for sports events is not rare. The
chess match between Russian Gary Kasparov and the IBM
supercomputer "Deep Blue" had been broadcasted live on an IBM web
site last May, drawing millions of fans worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
