<HEADLINE> Shanghai Uses Foreign Capital to Develop Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
metropolitan area, is currently home to 62 schools involving
funding from over 20 countries and regions, according to the
Shanghai municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Cooperative schools have emerged as a new area attracting
foreign investment over the past several years, according to an
official in charge of the city's education.
</P>
<P>
Overseas partners come from Britain, Japan, the United States,
France, Holland, Singapore, Canada, Australia and various other
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"The influx of foreign investment has enabled us to establish
more cooperative schools," said the official. "It will help narrow
the gap on education between China and developed countries."
</P>
<P>
He said that such schools in Shanghai have trained a large
number of senior management personnel with graduation certificates
widely recognized throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
He said, the municipal government recently issued special
regulations on the management of foreign-funded schools in order
to attract more overseas capital needed to promote local education.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Shanghai's rapidly developing economy has
created the need for more skilled personnel, especially in
commerce, finance, real estate, information processing and
industrial sectors which apply new high technology.
</P>
<P>
He added that from a third to half of shanghai's 1.25 million
professionals are expected to resign from their current jobs and
join the service industry.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that "the appearance of cooperative schools in
Shanghai has fulfilled the city's pressing demand for training
more skilled personnel for the new industries and the service
sector." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
