<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telephone Tariffs Cut in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's telephone tariffs,
one of the highest in the world, have been revised downwards and
will take effect from today, reported The Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
Sempala Mbuga, managing director of Uganda Posts and
Telecommunication Corporation (UPTC), was quoted as saying that
charges for calls to the frequently called countries such as
Kenya and Tanzania have been reduced by 40 percent from 3,000
Shillings (about 3 U.S. Dollars) to 1,800 Shillings (about 1.8
dollars) per minute.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to harmonise tariffs within the sub region,
charges for calls to east African countries have accordingly been
reduced.
</P>
<P>
Mbuga said UPTC is introducing a three-tier tariff structure
that includes standard, economy and super economy rates for local
and national calls.
</P>
<P>
Inland mail tariffs which have been unrealistically low have
generally been increased by 70 percent, while international rates
have been increased by 25 percent, he noted, adding that a
discount of 10 percent will be given on bulk posting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Delegation to Visit Kenya for Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is to send to Kenya a
high-powered delegation to discuss non-tariff barriers which are
said to be standing in the way of Ugandans selling their goods
across the border.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Trade and Industry Minister Henry Muganwa Kajura was
quoted by today's East African as saying that he will lead a
delegation to Nairobi this month to discuss issues "affecting
trade between the two sister countries."
</P>
<P>
The issues include the cash bond requirement imposed on those
importing transit goods through Kenya's Mombasa port and
allegations that Kenyan traders are placing obstacles in the path
of Ugandans who want to export goods to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The cash bonds requirement was introduced by the Kenya Revenue
Authority (KPA) to replace the much-abused insurance bonds as a
way of curbing the dumping of untaxed goods into the Kenyan
market.
</P>
<P>
But the new bonds have proved almost as ineffective as the
insurance bonds they replaced, as thousands of tons of illicit
sugar imported by well-connected businessmen finds its way into
the local market.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the Uganda Revenue Authority last May instituted
measures similar to those in Kenya to prevent dumping of goods
and which the Ugandans are protesting against.
</P>
<P>
Under the requirement imposed by both the KPA and its Ugandan
counterpart, all goods in transit must deposit with the
government money equivalent to the value of goods in transit.
</P>
<P>
Both Ugandan importers and members of the Uganda Clearing and
Forwarding Agents Association (UCFA) say the introduction of the
cash bond requirement by the Kenyan government was affecting
their operations.
</P>
<P>
"It's only clearing agents and big importers who have a lot of
money and who are not facing problems with the new system," said
a clearing agent in Kampala who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
Kajura said his delegation will also investigate complaints by
Ugandan traders that Kenyan business people were conniving with
some government officials to frustrate them.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a Kenyan governemnt policy, it is only a few
traders who are doing it," said Kajura.
</P>
<P>
Uganda manufacturers want to export products such as day-old
chicks from Ugachick, fish and mattresses to their eastern
African neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is Kenya's largest trading partner in eastern Africa.
Kenya's exports to Uganda were worth more than 160 million
Dollars last year, compared to only 40 million Dollars of
production coming from the opposite direction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
