<HEADLINE> Uganda Rebel Leader Back with 300 Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Rebel leader of the Lord's
Resistance Army Joseph Kony, has returned to northern Uganda with
his 300 soldiers, a senior army commander said Sunday in Gulu,
northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Colonel James Kazini, commander of the fourth division,
advised the residents in the northern district of Kitgum to avoid
Kony and his rebels in case of being abducted.
</P>
<P>
According to local report, LRA rebels abduct civilians to fill
its ranks.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan army was engaged in two battles last week with the
rebels, killing nine and capturing three of them. The government
troops will pursue the rebels, Kazini pledged.
</P>
<P>
The captured rebels said Kony's aim was to appear in the
country and show his presence. The Ugandan authorities had
recently celebrated the demise of IRA.
</P>
<P>
But the two battles scared Kony, forcing him to remain in the
border area near Sudan, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
A recent report said the LRA rebel group operating in the
north had some 450 members at present as against some 3,000
members in the past.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader entered Kitgum from southern Sudan where LRA
has its bases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
