<HEADLINE> S. Africa Offered to Re-equip Its Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Ministry
of Defense has confirmed that it had received several foreign
offers to modernize the aging equipment used by its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Local daily The Citizen quoted the military spokesman Puso
Tladi as saying that several countries including Britain and
Italy were competing to win the lucrative deal.
</P>
<P>
"There are many countries which are competing to re-equip our
armed forces, especially the navy and the air force which are
using archaic equipment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet and parliament have both approved the
modernization exercise, which will see the country enhancing its
capacity to protect its territory and airspace," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
According to sources reaching here at the weekend, Britain has
put together a 6.4-billion U.S. Dollar proposal to modernize the
South African troops which could be paid in gold.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Britain was competing with France and Germany
for the long-term arms supply deal, adding that South Africa was
unlikely to make a decision until next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
