<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Argentine soccer star Diego
Maradona said he had not taken cocaine, his agent Guillermo
Coppola told local television Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Coppola said, "Diego swore to me he did not take cocaine, so
now I doubt the results of the doping test."
</P>
<P>
Maradona tested positive for drugs after a league match for
Boca Juniors last Thursday and could be banned for up to five
years if a second test proves positive this week.
</P>
<P>
"Now Diego is at home with his daughters and family," Coppola
said. "He hasn't told me when he will speak (publicly) about the
(drugs) issue, but I'm sure he will do so when he's ready ... I
say we leave him alone and don't pressure him."
</P>
<P>
The Argentine Football Association (AFA) provisionally
suspended him Friday night and summoned him for a hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maradona, who has undergone several treatments to kick cocaine,
was attempting his fifth career comeback. He had tested postive
for drugs twice before, in 1991 when he was playing for Napoli and
during the 1994 World Cup in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
