<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army to Train University Graduates Into Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese army will launch a
one-year program to train university graduates into officers in a
move to give the army a more academic-oriented image.
</P>
<P>
The Shijiazhuang Army Academy, the biggest military school in
Asia, will recruit 140 university graduates this year, sources
close to the academy said, adding that these men will study
command skills at the academy.
</P>
<P>
Then they will be assigned command posts in combat troops,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
This is an important move to integrate higher education into
the training programs of the People's Liberation Army (PLA), and
to modernize the army which is being challenged by the global
hi-tech revolution, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
PLA has recruited college students before, but they were not
trained as commanding officers. Most of them were assigned to
non-combat posts or engaged in technical services.
</P>
<P>
The program was approved by the General Political Department
of the PLA, the sources revealed.
</P>
<P>
The 140 men majored in 20 specialities, including Chinese
literature, law, foreign languages, computer science and
sports. They are all under age 24.
</P>
<P>
During the one-year training, they will study various military
tactics and skills. Then they will be graded first lieutenant rank
and become platoon leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
