<HEADLINE> Sewage Water to Be Used for Afforestation in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The sewage water which has
been polluting Delhi residents' only sources of life, the Yamuna
river, for the past several decades, will now be utilized for
afforestation purposes, the Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
With life becoming more and more suffocating in the Indian
capital of Delhi due to the ever-increasing pollution, a review to
counter the choking city life was recently done in which
scientists expressed the need for effective use of sewage water
for development purpose.
</P>
<P>
Under a new project, the untreated sewage water which used to
join the Yamuna river through various drains would now be used for
afforestation.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities have allotted 40 acres of land for the
project for a period of one year.
</P>
<P>
If the project is successful implemented, it will not only
reduce discharge of sewage water into Yamuna but also help in
having green lung for Delhi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Experts Inspect Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Eleven overseas experts who
attended the 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies are wrapping
up a nine-day tour of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Experts from Taiwan, Britain, the United States, Australia and
New Zealand visited the Johkang Temple, the Potala Palace and the
Hospital of Tibetan Medicine. Many of them have been to Tibet
before.
</P>
<P>
They also plan to tour places of cultural or historical
interest such as Zhaxi Lhunbo Lamasery in Xigaze, the Xalu Temple,
the Baiqoi Monastery in Gyangze County, and Zongshan Mountain.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this century, Tibet people fought British
invaders at Zongshan Mountain for sovereignty of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Experts also plan to celebrate the Xodoin Festival with the
local citizens. Xodoin means "yoghurt banquet" in Tibetan
language, but the activity also features performance of Tibetan
dramas and programs highlighting Tibet's culture and economy.
</P>
<P>
Experts will also hold meetings with local residents to discuss
issues concerning Tibetan studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
