<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film on Opium War Makes Fine Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's expensive film has
turned in a big profit in Shanghai, beating all imported Hollywood
movies hands down.
</P>
<P>
"The Opium War", directed by Xie Jin, has generated box-office
sales of 14 million yuan (1.8 million US dollars) since its June
21 premiere in China's biggest commercial and trade metropolis.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that this is the highest amount taken in by a
single film in Shanghai's film history.
</P>
<P>
The film depicts Britain's invasion of China in 1840 after
China seized and burned opium smuggled in by British traders. The
war ended badly for China and signaled the beginning of the fall
of the eastern empire.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the number of enthusiastic moviegoers was so
big that cinema managers had to open additional viewing halls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
