<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Fund Its Own Budget in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda shall be able to fund
its own budget by the year 2002 from taxes, reported the local
daily The Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
Larbi Siaw, commissioner general of Uganda Revenue Authority
(URA), was quoted as saying "I know it is not easy to make
predictions in matters of revenue but I am tempted to say that
given Uganda's trend in tax improvement, it shall be able to
solely fund its financial budget by the year 2002."
</P>
<P>
Siaw, a Ghanaian who has been in Uganda for 6 years said, "I
saw a devastated country emerging from the shadows of 20 years of
war with an inflation rate of over 400 percent, a country whose
people were willing to come out of a dark."
</P>
<P>
Uganda's revenue collection has improved from 140 billion
Shillings (about 140 million U.S. Dollars) in 1991 to 742 billion
Shillings (about 742 million Dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
URA is expected to bag 851 billion Shillings (about 851
million Dollars) in 1997-1998 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Tumusime Mutebile, secretary to the Treasury, disclosed that
Uganda's taxes are at their highest and the government can only
revise them downwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 07:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divorce Rises 9.1 Percent in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran recorded a 9.1 percent rise
in divorce rate in the first quarter of the current Iranian
calendar year starting from March 21 over that of last year, a
government agency said here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,600 divorce cases were registered in the period,
the country's Statistics and Registration Administration said. But
it did not elaborate the causes for the rise.
</P>
<P>
Specialists attribute high divorce rate to economic pressures
as incomes are very low and inflation reaching 50-70 percent yearly.
</P>
<P>
A woman specialist said about 80 to 90 percent of the woman are
not satisfactory with their marriage not only for economic reasons
but for the negligence of their husbands as well.
</P>
<P>
According to the government agency, more than 130,000 couples
got married in the first quarter, four percent growth against that
in the same period last year. 
</P>
