<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Opening for Northwest Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The governor of China's Shaanxi
province has said no time will be waisted in making use of the
central government's new strategic policy of developing China's
backward western part.
</P>
<P>
The province will use more overseas investment and local
resources for economic development, Cheng Andong told Xinhua
recently.
</P>
<P>
The governor cited infrastructure, natural resource
exploration, agriculture, hi-tech industry and tourism as the
sectors which need investment urgently.
</P>
<P>
Before 2000, Shaanxi plans to build three railways, three
high-grade highways, and a number of coal, power, oil, gas and
mineral projects, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
The province, rich in resources, has plans for the
biggest gasfield with proven reserves of 210 billion cu.m. and one
of the largest fine coal mines in the world. The coal mine has
more than 160 billion tons of proven reserves.
</P>
<P>
The province is referred to as a "history museum", with its
35,000 historical sites and tourism potential, Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
It also ranks third in China in number of educational and
research institutions, with 56 universities and over 1,000
research bodies.
</P>
<P>
It has also made big progress in opening-up, Cheng noted. Since
the late 1970s, Shaanxi has set up 2,500 foreign-funded projects,
with total foreign capital of three billion US dollars. Last year,
it accelerated the pace of using overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, foreign investors bought 51 percent of the Weihe Power
Plant and 20-year management rights to an expressway from Xi'an,
the provincial capital, to Lintong, a city in eastern Shaanxi.
</P>
</TEXT>
