<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Levels Maintained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in China
this year will equal the amount attracted from overseas in
1996, Beijing-based English language newspaper "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistical Bureau (SSB) predicted a considerable
increase on State plans to use roughly 30 billion US dollars of
foreign direct investment this year. China absorbed over 40
billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China has been the world's second largest user of foreign direct
investment for four consecutive years. The United States ranks the
first.
</P>
<P>
An official of SSB's trade department pointed out that most
major investors in China, including Japan, the United States,
Singapore, South Korea, Britain and Germany all increased their
actual input in the first half of this year. But new investment is
growing at a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of foreign direct investment from January to June
still go to the eastern coastal areas despite the government's
call for a shift to the west and the north.
</P>
<P>
However, Shanghai, Guangdong, Guangxi, Shandong and Hainan
provinces saw a drop in new foreign investment in the first six
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Investors are being allowed to enjoy reductions of exemption on
tariffs on imported equipment worth less than 30 million US
dollars for another year, according to the deputy director of the
SSB's trade department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
