<HEADLINE> India Denies Plan for Indo-Pakistan Summit in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
clarified that Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral will not hold any
talks with his Pakistan counterpart Nawaz Sharif in New York
during his visit to the United States later this month, the local
press said today.
</P>
<P>
The clarification came on Sunday, one day after the prime
minister reportedly said that he would hold talks with Sharif
during their presence in New York to attend the forthcoming
session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
An official spokesman said on Sunday that the media reports to
this effect were "misleading".
</P>
<P>
The prime minister during a brief exchange with the media at
Shantiniketan (West Bengal of India) on Saturday had only
mentioned about the proposed foreign secretary level talks between
India and Pakistan, the spokesman said, adding that "there was no
mention of talks at the prime ministers' level."
</P>
<P>
Several Indian newspapers had quoted Gujral as saying on
Saturday that "I am going to hold talks with Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif in New York. Indo-Pakistan relations are
improving. We are hopeful that all our aspirations for improved
bilateral relations would be fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
Gujral, who is scheduled to go to New York in the third week of
September to address the UN General Assembly, is expected to meet
U.S. President Bill Clinton on September 22.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who will be present on the same day in New York, will
also meet President Clinton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
