<HEADLINE> Committee Set Up to Help Foreigners Learn Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China has set up a committee
to help foreigners who want to take the Chinese Proficiency Test,
today's People's Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The test, known in Chinese as "Hanyu Shuiping Kaoshi" or "HSK,"
has been taken by 80,000 foreigners from 115 countries and regions
since 1988, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The new committee aims to strengthen the leadership in this
field and safeguard the superiority of the test, it says. Wei Yu,
deputy director of the State Education Committee, is head of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
The test is given three times a year -- in January, May and
July. According to the results, examinees will be awarded
certificates ranging from levels 1-11.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the craze to learn Chinese is a result of
the increased exchanges between China and foreign countries, as
well as the country's successful reform and opening up drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
