<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Experiences Hottest Summer in 100 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sweden, which is normally
famous for its pleasant cool summers of the Nordic region,
experienced the hottest summer in more than 100 years this year.
</P>
<P>
Stockholm had an average temperature of 19 degrees Celsius from
June to August, three degrees higher than in normal years and
above the record high of 18.9 degrees Celsius in 1900.
</P>
<P>
In Southern and central Sweden, the average temperature in
August this year was 21-22 degrees Celsius, five to six degrees
higher than in normal years, which is also two degrees higher than
that in Paris.
</P>
<P>
As a result, electric fans or air-conditioners have been widely
used in many offices and residence houses since early July.
</P>
<P>
The sustained heat spell has caused storms. In the northern
Piteaa area, the precipitation on July 28 reached 198 mm, which
was the heaviest rainfall on a single day in Sweden since 1873.
</P>
<P>
There was no exact account for the freak summer this year in
Sweden and the whole Scandinavia. Experts were reluctant to say
whether the abnormal weather conditions were a result of the
impact of "greenhouse effect" or the "El Nino" phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
