<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0300 GMT, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai industries are seeking as much as 60 billion
baht (1.76 billion US dollars) from the Industry Ministry, 10
times the amount the central bank is prepared to provide.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of companies in the country are facing severe cash
flow problems. Even those with firm orders in hand cannot obtain
loans to buy raw materials or expand production, the Bangkok Post
today quotes Deputy Industry Minister Somphop Amatayakul as
saying.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Sunday went to church
together with his family to mourn the death of Princess Diana but
has not decided whether to attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
"We liked her very much. We admired her work for children, for
people with AIDS, for the cause of ending the scourge of land
mines in the world," Clinton told reporters before he and his
vacationing family headed to church in Edgartown, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
"We can only hope that her work will go forward and that
everyone who can will support her two fine sons and help them to
have the life and the future that she would want," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian President Hafez Assad here Sunday discussed
the Middle East peace process with the visiting Middle East envoy
of the European Union Miguel Angel Moratinos.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, attended by Syrian Freign Minister Farouk
Shara, Assad also discussed with Moratinos the international
efforts to overcome the obstacles put by the Israeli government,
according to a presidential spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Assad had stressed the importance of an
active European role in the peace efforts as well as Syria's
adherence to a just and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy briefed the Syrian leader about the European
efforts to activate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In reaction to Egypt's sentencing of Israeli
citizen Azzam Azzam for espionage, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Sunday said that Azzam was innocent and should be
released immediately.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who was informed of the verdict in Azzam's trial
this morning during the weekly Cabinet meeting, said in a
statement that he and the whole government viewed the verdict as
"a very serious development."
</P>
<P>
"Azzam Azzam is innocent and should not sit in prison even for
one day," said Netanyahu, adding that he had sent a message to
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak last week asking the latter to
act to secure Azzam's release.
</P>
<P>
Azzam, the 35-year-old Druse from Maghar in the Galilee, was
sentenced by Egypt's State Security Court in Cairo earlier Sunday
to 15 years in prison with hard labor for spying for Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
