<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Civil Aviation in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's civil aviation
business will grow at an annual rate of 12 percent in the
remaining years of this century, according to Chen Guangyi,
Director of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, air transport volume will reach 14 billion
ton kilometers. The country's airlines will carry 100 million
passengers and two million tons of goods and mail, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
"We have to open more air routes, add advanced aircraft, and
build a batch of key airports and air control facilities to raise
the capacity of civil aviation," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Before the arrival of the 21st century, China will do its
utmost to build and upgrade 41 airports, whose combined handling
capacity will account for 95 percent of the country's total, to cater
to the demand expected in the years from 2005 to 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
The airports are scattered in 40 municipalities, provincial
capitals, capital cities of autonomous regions, and important
economic showcase and tourism cities.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that emphasis will be put on the expansion of
the Beijing Capital Airport, construction of the Shanghai Pudong
International Airport and Guangzhou's New Baiyun International
Airport, and the renovation of Shanghai Hongqiao International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese civil aviation industry is entering a new
era of development, and its growth continues to exceed the world
average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
