<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Inland Water Transport Improves: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Minister for Transport
Lieutenant-General Thein Win said today that his country's inland
water transport has greatly improved due to addition of over 100
cargo and passenger vessels in the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
Thein Win made the remarks at a vessel delivery ceremony here
today, attended by First Secretary of the Myanmar State Law and
Order Restoration Council Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt and Second
Secretary Lieutenant-General Tin Oo.
</P>
<P>
The minister said of the added 103 vessels, 72 were purchased
from China, while 31 others built domestically.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar's state-run Five Star Line Co. signed one
more contract in September 1996 with China National Machinery and
Equipment Import and Export Corporation on purchasing two ocean
going multi-purpose cargo vessels to enhance the country's
overseas water transport.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also built a number of freighter vessels for
foreign companies in recent years which include those in Indonesia
and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
