<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Civil Aviation in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China implemented the policy of reform and opening-up in
the late 1970s, the country's civil aviation business skyrocketed
20.1 percent annually for 15 consecutive years, 3.6 times higher
than the average figure of member countries of the International
Aviation Organization.
</P>
<P>
The aggregate aviation transport volume amounted to 8.05
billion ton kilometers in 1996, ranking 10th in the world, as
against 12th in 1992. Passenger volume was 55.55 million, double
the figure of 1992 and jumping from ninth to fifth place.
</P>
<P>
"The increase was larger than in any five-year period in the
past," the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, China invested as much as 40
billion yuan in building airports, air routes and support
facilities, as well as technical renovation.
</P>
<P>
The country has set up the world's largest flying institute,
Asia's largest computer booking network, and Asia's largest
hangar. Construction, expansion and upgrading have also been
completed on 39 key airports, including those in Shenzhen, Guilin,
Guiyang, Fuzhou, and Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that more than 440 transport airplanes are now
operating, up about 130 in 1992. The world's most advanced
airplanes can be seen in the Chinese aviation fleet, he added.
</P>
<P>
A fairly complete aviation network has been formed in China, he
said, noting that the country now has about 880 air routes, 260
more than five years ago. Its international air routes are linked
with more than 60 cities in 32 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
