<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Limits Dollar Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Indonesia
has imposed a five-million-U.S.-dollar limit on the forward
foreign exchange trading to confine speculative dollar buying,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The new move, which was announced on Sunday by the bank in a
statement, came into effect on August 29, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the trading of foreign currencies from
domestic banks to non-resident customers would be limited to five
million U.S. dollars per customer.
</P>
<P>
The only exception would be swap transaction for investment in
Indonesia and import/export needs, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Forward exchange transactions are purchases or sales of foreign
currencies at an exchange rate established at the time of the deal
but with payment and delivery at a specified future date.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following de factor devaluation
of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso in July.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Central Bank, in its first move following the
attacks, widened its now defunct intervention band from 8 percent
to 12 percent to make speculation on rupiah more expensive.
</P>
<P>
But the widening band was not effective to appease speculation.
After intervening in the market with 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, the
Central Bank decided to float the currency on August 14.
</P>
<P>
After the floating, the rupiah suddenly fell to a historic low
of 3,045 against the U.S. dollar, which prompted the Central Bank
to squeeze rupiah liquidity and raise interest rates to discourage
speculative dollar buying using cheap rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah recovered briefly to 2,650 after the Central Bank
squeezed liquidity by raising the Central Bank's Certificate (SBI)
rates to as high as 30 percent for one-month paper, stopping to
discount money market securities and forced state companies to
convert their deposits to the Central Bank's papers.
</P>
<P>
But the currency continued to fluctuate, dropping to the same
level before the Central Bank imposed the credit crunch, and even
touched a new historic low of 3,070 last Friday before easing to
2,900 level.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers said the Central Bank's newest move of limiting
forward transactions would not stop the rupiah from weakening
further. It would only slow down the process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
