<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok to Host Asia-Europe Finance Ministers' Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The first Asia-Europe finance
ministers' meeting will be held in Bangkok on September 19, it is
learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to be held in line with decisions made at the
first Asia-Europe meeting (ASEM) in Bangkok in March 1996 to
discuss monetary and fiscal policy cooperation between the two
regions.
</P>
<P>
At the forthcoming meeting, finance ministers from 25 countries
will discuss financial cooperation between the two continents and
customs cooperation under the ASEM framework.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is expected to report on progress toward a
single currency.
</P>
<P>
Asian member countries are concerned about how the European
monetary unit, scheduled to be implemented in January 1999, will
affect capital, financial and foreign-exchange markets in Europe
and consequently in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Asia will also call for more investment from Europe,
particularly infrastructure financing in Indochina, according to a
Thai official.
</P>
<P>
Linkages of financial information among the 25 member states
will also be discussed, in order to establish an E-mail network
similar to what the APEC (Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation)
finance ministers are doing, the official said.
</P>
<P>
ASEM groups seven ASEAN members, three ASEAN dialogue partners
(China, Japan and South Korea) and the 15 European Union members.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
