<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Industries Seek More Money Than Bank's Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Thai industries are seeking as
much as 60 billion baht (1.76 billion US dollars) from the
Industry Ministry, 10 times the amount the central bank is
prepared to provide.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of companies in the country are facing severe cash
flow problems. Even those with firm orders in hand cannot obtain
loans to buy raw materials or expand production, the Bangkok Post
today quotes Deputy Industry Minister Somphop Amatayakul as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank was committed to providing 6 billion
baht (176 million dollars) in loans, but the requests from 248
applicants over the past month topped 60 billion baht (1.76
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said companies seeking fund to increase production would
receive priority in the screening process, but those asking for
money to refinance or to invest in the stock market will be
rejected.
</P>
<P>
The inability of some companies to secure raw materials has
resulted in lost export opportunities totaling more than one
billion baht, according to the Federation of Thai Industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
