<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossilized Animals Found in Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
unearthed the fossilized remains of a group of animals dating to
20,000 years ago in southern China.
</P>
<P>
A large quantity of bones of giant pandas, monkeys and stegodon
orientalises, which belong to the elephant family, were recovered
in a village in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The experts pointed out that many of the animals lived together
with primitive man through the Old Stone Age to the Neo-Stone Age,
and their fossils can provide important clues for the study of
ancient environment, climate and geography in southern China.
</P>
</TEXT>
