<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chain Stores in North China City Grow Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin had 61 companies with about 1,000 outlets by the end of
last June, with 16,000 employees and an average of 100 million
yuan (12 million US dollars) in monthly sales.
</P>
<P>
International companies are also getting involved.
China Resources Holdings of Hong Kong, for example, has 13 outlets in
Tianjin. The Daier Corporation, a major Japanese retailer, has
five supermarkets, each covering 2,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Also engaged in the chain-store business are some of the
most-famous local business like Gou Bu Li Restaurant, a steamed bun
operation with 80 franchises inside and outside China.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the chain stores and supermarkets are increasingly
popular with local consumers, and have great potential for future
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
