<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIG Chief Calls for Further Development of Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, August 31 (Xinhua) -- President of the International
Gymnastics Federation Bruno Grandi Sunday called for further
development of gymnastics in order to keep the sport event alive.
</P>
<P>
The FIG president told a press conference held just before the
1997 World Gymnastics Championships began Sunday evening in the
Olympic capital of Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
"The codes of point now are not difficult," said Grandi, who
became the FIG president last year. "They are far behind the
development of the event of gymnastics." He urged further reform
but blamed no one on the current situation of gymnastics lagging
behind technically.
</P>
<P>
Grandi pledged that his federation would give support for
strong federations to make gymnastics among top sports events. On
the other hand, he said, the FIG would also support those
federations underdeveloped by providing them with means and funds
of training.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the FIG's refusal of six federations to take
part in the competition in Lausanne, Grandi said that every
federation should be treated equally.
</P>
<P>
Being a former gymnastist, Grandi said that he knew well the
feelings of those who were unable to come to Lausanne, but the
regulations and rules should be respected at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Applications of six federations, including those of Bulgaria,
Egypt, Zimbabwe, Mexico and two other Latin American countries,
were turned down because they came behind the deadline or after
the drawing of lots on June 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
