<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bad Media Behavior Accused For Diana's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, Aug 31 (Xinhua) - Media which made check news are
accused for the death of British Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
Diana, 36, and her companion Dodi Al Fayed, 41, were killed
early Sunday when their car crashed while being chased through
Paris by photographers on motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Diana's brother Earl Charles Spencer said he always believed
the press would kill his sister, but that he had never imagined
"they would take such a direct hand in her death".
</P>
<P>
"It would appear that every proprietor and editor of every
publication that has paid for intrusive and exploitative
photographs of her, encouraging greedy and ruthless individuals to
risk everything in pursuit of Diana's image, has blood on his
hands today," Spencer told the media outside his house in Cape
Town in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said he was dismayed at the
sudden death of Princess Diana, while blaming a section of the
media for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
"Princess Diana has also become the victim of an increasingly
brutal and unscrupulous competitive fight of a section of the
media. This terrible accident and her death should finally give
those responsible in the media something to think about," Kohl
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Check news is popular in the west where publishers often buy
news to promote circulation of their products.
</P>
<P>
There are more than a dozen tabloids in Britain with
circulation of the top five overtaking one million respectively,
compared with the total circulation of five qualified newspapers
such as The Times just reaching three million.
</P>
<P>
"We have all they have, we also have all they don't have," a
vice chief editor of a leading tabloid told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't buy some photos, others will do," he said,
referring to a fierce competition among the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
Diana has become public figure since the disclosure of her
romance with Prince Charles. Tabloids have spent millions to buy
her photos and some photographers thus made millionaires.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Mirror bought photos by an Italian paparazzi named Mario
Brenna for about 250, 000 pounds (420,000 U.S. dollars) three weeks
before the disclosure of the romance between Diana and Dodi Fayed.
</P>
<P>
French criminal police questioned seven photographers who were
following Diana's car.
</P>
<P>
Legal sources said they could face charges of endangering lives
if they were proved to have caused the car to drive at high speed.
</P>
<P>
They could also be accused of failing to assist persons in
danger if they were found to have snapped pictures of the crash
rather than helping the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
