<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin Ready to Replace Welfare with Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Wisconsin, a state which has
led welfare reform in the United States, is asking everybody to
work as of Labor Day tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The state's latest welfare program -- "Wisconsin Works,"
requires all able-bodied adults to work or get job training in
exchange for a check, food stamps, medical assistance and
subsidized child care. It also puts a five-year cap on benefits,
the Associated Press reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The program follows a decade of welfare experiments, starting
with Learnfare, which reduced benefits for recipients whose
children skipped school.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the state has tried out various measures to reform
welfare.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, when the federal government overhauled regulations for
welfare program carried out by the states, Wisconsin was the first
to apply and the first to receive approval for its work-focused
proposal.
</P>
<P>
The state welfare caseload had been reduced by 62 percent, from
100,000 families to 38,000 families. Until Monday, those families
were receiving assistance through the Aid to Families with
Dependent Children.
</P>
<P>
The state can extend the time limits for families that are
cooperative but unable to become self-sufficient, said Jean
Rogers, administrator of the state Division of Economic Support.
</P>
<P>
Advocates for the poor worry there will not be enough
low-skilled jobs or child care available, and that jobs will not
pay enough. They fear that when benefits run out, homeless
shelters, food pantries and other charities will be the only
safety net. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970901.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry Money Flowing to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The tobacco industry lobbying
for Congressional approval of a proposed 368-billion-U.S. dollar
settlement in a class lawsuit reached in June in 40 states, has
kept up a steady flow of campaign money to the lawmakers it is
courting.
</P>
<P>
Leading tobacco industry political action committees (PAC)
funneled 566,721 dollars to pivotal lawmakers in the first six
months of the year, according to Federal Election Commission
reports compiled by the nonprofit Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
The PAC is a group that represents a point of view and parcels
out campaign money to lawmakers or candidates sharing that point
of view.
</P>
<P>
That giving came on top of two million dollars in "soft money".
Nearly 80 percent of the total went to the Republicans who control
both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
Top recipients of the contributions included key Republican
legislators of both houses, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
